<dl id="n12043h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12043h">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12043h"> 43(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ wolf or friar 4<sup>d</sup> each <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12043h"><li>FW 99.14f </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n12043h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n12043h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12043h">MS BL 47472-161</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:061 <a name="d23d" href="../../ff/fdra/dda.htm#d23d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/d23d.htm#n12043h">Draft: I.4&sect;2.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">By God&apos;s Providence the faith of Erin was put to the test, and tried in the crucible. The foe and the stranger visited the peaceful shores of Erin <font color="green">[&ldquo;]</font> No church or altar was left in the land; the holy Sacrifice was offered at night, or at dawn of day, in the bog or on the mountain; a rude stone serving as an altar, and the canopy the vast expanse of the heavens. Some priests found shelter in the homes of their faithful flock; but the great majority were put to the sword or exiled. The same price was laid upon the head of a wolf or friar. <small> Very Rev. Dean Kinane, <a name="TKSP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#TKSP"><cite title="source">St. Patrick: his life, his heroic virtues, his labours, and the fruits of his labours</cite></a>, (ed. unknown) 184-5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
